_prev_prog_2.Description:
An Accidental Release Prevention Program is in place to minimize the risk of hazardous chemical releases in accordance with USEPA Risk Management Program (40 CFR Part 68) requirements.  This prevention program covers those processes that handle regulated substances above the threshold amount. The prevention program provides a structured approach to preventing accidents. Some of the specific activities in the prevention program include:

?    Process safety information is accessible at all times;
?    A hazard review was conducted as part of the preparations for RMP compliance;
?    Written operating procedures are used for training and guiding the work of the operators;
?    Training is provided to all employees that operate the system;
?    A program is in place to properly maintain the system and equipment;
?    Incidents are investigated and actions are taken as part of a continuous improvement effort; and 
?    Routine audits are conducted to assure that safe practices are being followed

The processes at the facility subject to RMP are designed with extensive safeguards to protect against the accidental release of a hazardous material. An example of safety equipment in place includes foam fire suppression systems. 

In addition, process operators receive extensive training in the safe operation of the process, and are required to follow detailed operating procedures to help ensure safety. The facility has also implemented a maintenance program to monitor the physical condition of the process equipment, and replace or repair equipment before it fails.

In the unlikely event of a spill or a release involving a hazardous material, the facility has developed an emergency response plan providing the procedures to be followed to minimize the potential impacts of a fire from the facility. In the event of a release, the facility will call the Bedford Park Fire Department located at the facility boundary.

